<P>Clari&s;&s;a was next day &s;o ill, that Mrs. Smith provided for her a very good nur&s;e; and &s;he had al&s;o the voluntary attendance of Mrs. Lovick, a decayed widow gentlewoman of great piety, who lodged over <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">er apart|ment, and of whom Clari&s;&s;a &s;oon became ex|tremely fond. In the evening was called in a &s;kilful and eminent apotheca<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">y; and a few days after, Mr. Belford prevailed on her to accept of the vi&s;its of Doctor H&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> phy&s;ician no le&s;s eminent for his humanity and affectionate behaviour, than for his kill in phy&s;ick.</P>
<P><PB N="105" REF="029413_0107_0FE0F28F2034DF80">
