<P>The &s;ufferings of Clari&s;&s;a had been more than her tender frame could bear; &s;he grad|ually d<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">clined, and her illne&s;s daily <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ncrea&s;ed. In this melancholy &s;ituation, deprived of the comfort and a&s;&s;i&s;tance of her relations, &s;he found con&s;olation in the tenderne&s;s of the worthy Mrs. Lovick and Mrs. Smith, which &s;he termed maternal; and in the affectionate vi&s;its both of her doctor and apothecary, who being in years, and having children of their own grown up, behaved to her with an affection which &s;he was plea&s;ed to call pa|ternal. Death now making its gradual ap|proaches, &s;he &s;ubdued her re&s;entments, and offered up &s;ome of her petitions for him
