<P>Mr. Morden having tran&s;cribed the&s;e pa&s;|&s;ages, he the next day procured a general meeting with all the family, and renewed his &s;olicitations in favour of Clari&s;&s;a: He then expatiated on her penitence, virtue, and ill health; read a very contrite letter written by Lovelace to Clari&s;&s;a, with her high-&s;oul'd an&s;wer; and afterward mention|ing his vi&s;it to Mi&s;s Howe, read &s;ome of the pa&s;&s;ages he had tran&s;cribed from Clari&s;&s;a's letters to that lady; particularly one, in
